ce:section.ce:para:
To improve the efficiency of ORR in different categories of fuel cells, it is important to develop a highly active ORR catalyst that can work in alkaline, neutral, and acidic electrolytes. Wang et al. (Wang et al., 2020a) prepared a carbon-based electrocatalyst by treating the coconut leaves with KOH/KHCO3 as an activator with the help of an ultrasonic auxiliary method which contains pyridine-N and graphite-N in its structure. This catalyst contributed to limiting current densities of 5.50, 5.45, and 4.97 mA/cm2 in alkaline, neutral, and acidic electrolytes, respectively, achieving versatility over a wide pH range and even surpassing the baseline Pt/C catalyst (Wang et al., 2020a). Furthermore, since OER and ORR occur simultaneously in various energy conversion and storage devices, it is highly desirable to fabricate efficient novel bifunctional catalysts to overcome the problems of slow kinetics and excessive overpotentials (Sekhon et al., 2022; Tang et al., 2022). BCMs are quite active in the field of bifunctional catalysts and have also performed parallelly in many cases (
                           Kim et al., 2021; Xiao et al., 2020
                           ).
